This adds grammars that handle XML Schema 1.0 regular expressions
as defined in http://www.w3.org/TR/2004/REC-xmlschema-2-20041028/.

handled in character groups, we borrow parts of XML Schema 1.1
clarifications to provide unsurprising results.

Removed the extra grammar files and detailed the steps needed to successful have the port running and generating in the README.

[javascript/Go] fix compile time error

The error was caused because ANTLR4 generates 2 constructors for each RuleContext in the grammar: `New[RuleName]Context` and `NewEmpty[RuleName]Context`.

This caused a conflict since the grammar defines a `statement` and `emptyStatement` rule. Thus generating function names `NewStatementContext, NewEmptyStatementContext, NewEmptyStatementContext, NewEmptyEmptyStatementContext`.

The error was fixed by simply adding an underscore (_) to the `emptyStatement` rule.

Port of the grammar to Go. More detailed information in the `javascript/Go/README.md` file.

golang: Fixed issue parsing structures with functionType parameters

golang: Fixed issue parsing structures with functionType parameters

The `signature` of `functionType` was improperly picking up its optional result from the next line and consequently failing with "no viable alternative at input ...". In this case the parser should ignore anything after the line feed. Correction simply invoked the existing predicate to verify no line terminator exists after function parameters and providing an alternative that has no result. Example `struct_with_func_type.go` provided.

Merge pull request #1136 from rovarga/xpath-qname

xpath: fix qName/functionName rules

xpath: fix qName/functionName rules

Parser grammar is incorrect in its definition of QName, which is
taken to be constrained the way FunctionName is -- to exclude
NodeType. This means that NameTest and VariableReference do not
accept legal values.

Fix this by having nCName rule contain NodeType, automatically
fixing all users of qName rule and breaking functionName.
functionName is reformulated without using qName and spelling out
the two alternatives of PrefixedName and UnprefixedName -- excluding
NodeType from UnprefixedName case.

Signed-off-by: Robert Varga <nite@hq.sk>

Disallow control characters in string fields

According to the [ECMA-404](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf)  standard, strings cannot contain control characters U+0000 to U+001F in addition to the characters `"` and `\`.

> #### 9. String
> ... 
> All code points may be placed within the quotation marks except for the code points that must be escaped: quotation mark (U+0022), > reverse solidus (U+005C), and the control characters U+0000 to U+001F.
> ... 

Therefore, some changes have been made to conform to the spec.

Fixes sci notation and unary +/-

Scientific notations now do not accept spaces within them. Furthermore, unary operators (i.e., +, -) can now be chained (e.g., +--+1 = ---b) is now accepted.

Prevent variables and numbers with spaces

Because white spaces are suppressed, having the following rules:

number
   : MINUS? DIGIT + (POINT DIGIT +)?
   ;
DIGIT
   : ('0' .. '9')
   ;
MINUS
   : '-'
   ;
POINT
   : '.'
   ;
WS
   : [ \r\n\t] + -> channel (HIDDEN)
   ;
 will lead to the acceptance of numbers with spaces such 1 2 3

Add MySQL grammar. All tests successfull

Correct parsing of variable statements that are arrays with a type hint

The type hint on variable declarations come after the ambiguous identifier but the existing rule had it being parsed after any array dimensions which is incorrect.

Fix parsing of default values for an argument that are enumeration values

The parser rule for handling default values of an argument only handled literals or identifiers, but a default value can be an enumeration value or a field in another type such as

Private Sub Test(Optional ByVal foo As enmSomeEnum = enmSomeEnum.Bar)

So change the parser rule for argDefaultValue to use valueStmt to parse the value part.

Fix parsing of With expressions in the presence of "New ..."

The expression as part of a With statement can be a new object rather than an existing variable reference - e.g.

With New SomeClass
...

But the withStmt rule wasn't allowing for the New keyword and resulted in parse errors.

Handle parsing of control arrays within a form

Control array properties of the form

TabPicture(0) = "SomeForm.frx":08CA
Tab(0).ControlEnabled= 0 'False
Tab(0).Control(0)= "Frame1"

Was causing parse errors so update cp_PropertyName rule to handle these cases.

Merge pull request #768 from mshockwave/master

Fix Symbol Names Conflicts

Fix Rule Names Conflicts

  - Fix rule names that conflicts with cpp targets
    by simply adding 'the' as prefix

Allow whitespace around string concatenation & operator to be optional

This allows parsing of string concatenation where the different parts are split over multiple lines as in

x = "foo" _
& "bar"

Which previously resulted in a parse error.

Handle parsing of module references which are references to VBP files

A module reference may be a path to a VBP project file of the form

Object = "*\A..\..\SomeFile.vbp"

Which wasn't previously handled and resulted in parse errors.

Additional correction to parsing of a form control's property

A property value may start with a ^, e.g.

Shortcut = ^F

Since the part of cp_SingleProperty is getting a bit unwieldy split out the parsing of the value component into a separate rule.

Allow trailing colon after On Error GoTo <valueStmt>

It's acceptable for a trailing colon to be present on the name of the label used in an On Error GoTo statement, e.g.

On Error GoTo ErrorHandler:

But this wasn't being handled and resulted in parse errors.

Ignore whitespace after a '.' in an explicit call statement

Code of the form

Call foo.bar. _
baz(, , abc, xyz)

Was rejected with a parse error due to the whitespace after the '.'. Fixed by ignoring whitespace between the '.' and the final part of the call expression.

Merge pull request #766 from maybeec/patch-1

Java8: fix unused packageName production
fix unused packageName production

Allow a form control's property value to be brace enclosed.

It's possible for the value of a form control property to be enclosed within {}  - e.g.

Begin VB.Menu mnuContents
         Caption         =   "&Contents      "
         Shortcut        =   {F1}
End

But this wasnt previously handled and resulted in parse errors.

Use lexer token names in a few of the form control properties rules.

Replaces usages of character constants.

Fix parsing of nested procedure calls that return an array

It's possible for a nested procedure call to return an array which is subsequently indexed as to produce a parameter value to an outer procedure call - i.e.

If IsNull(SomeFuncReturningArray(bar)(0)) Then
End If

But the grammar wasn't handling that and the resulting parser rejected the code.

Fixed by adding a new rule which is almost identical to ICS_S_ProcedureOrArrayCall (to avoid left-recursive errors) to handle parsing the nested procedure call and using that in ICS_S_ProcedureOrArrayCall

Allow whitespace in a chain of member call sequences

Code may be written as

If .CellSet(0) _
    .Value = 0 Then

End If

But the whitespace following the _ in the chain of member call expressions causes a parser error so allow leading whitespace before the ".".

Can't just skip leading whitespace on the following line as this may be syntactically important in some cases.

Implement parsing of octal literals

Octal literals of the form "&O123" were not implemented and resulted in parser errors.

VB6 grammar improvements and bug fixes
Implement parsing of the set of control's and their properties that can be present within a .frm file and any nested controls contained within.

Fix parsing of module option statements interspersed with declarations

It's valid to have module option statements (Option Explicit etc.)  before and after top-level declarations but this was causing a compiler error.

Adjust the moduleBodyElement rule to also allow module options to be parsed as part of the body.

Visibility adjustments for Enum and Const statements

Not all visibilities are valid for Enum and Const statements so introduce some new rules for only accepting those which are allowed and use them in enumerationStmt and constStmt.

Handle type hints on argument declarations

Type hints on argument declarations wasn't being handled and was missing type hints for ! and @ on integral and floating-point types.

Fix parsing of While...Wend loops with blank lines at the end of the loop body

While...Wend loops of the form

While True

      DoEvents

  Wend

Were causing a compiler error due to the new line at the end of the loop body so tweak the whileWendStmt to handle this.

Fix parsing for For...Next loops in the presence of a type hint

Restrict LineTerminators in ECMAScript grammars.

Restrict LineTerminators in ECMAScript grammars.

According to the ECMAScript 5.1 Standard (and the comments in the existing
ANTLR grammars) LineTerminator is not allowed between a 'return', 'throw',
'break' or 'continue' keyword and the following Identifier or Expression
or between a LeftHandSideExpression and a postfix operator. However,
while the latter case is handled correctly, this restriction is missing
from the prior one. The patch fixes this.

VB6: Added Select Case test cases with multiple expressions

Missing Select Case use cases

As reported in the official language reference, `Select Case` cases can have multiple expressions per case: https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa266274(v=vs.60).aspx

The current grammar fails to parse this valid case (copied from the above link):
   `Case 1 To 4, 7 To 9, 11, 13, Is > MaxNumber`

The proposed change separates `Case Else` from "normal" cases, and allows comma concat between different expressions.

The current grammar fails to parse range expressions (`Case Value1 To Value2`) when X is a generic value statement, not necessarily a number.

CPP14.g4 bugfix - relational ops in template arguments

Consider the signature
void TestFunc(vector< ClassA > args, vector < ClassB > args2)

Right now this is parsed as 
- a declaration of a variable args2 
- the type of args2 is vector <A, B> 
    where A = (ClassA > args) 
               B = (vector < B) 
   i.e. a a template instantiation that has two relational expressions that are the arguments

This stems from the priority order of the template argument list which is 
templateargument : constantexpression | typeid | idexpression;

Changing the order to : typeid | constantexpression| idexpression; fixes this.

Tested that this is the same behavior as observed in Microsoft c++ compiler, gcc, clang and icc.

Merge pull request #372 from swenson/master

JSON grammar fix: json can be any value

JSON grammar fix: json can be any value

The ECMA-404 standard says

> A JSON text is a sequence of tokens formed from Unicode code points
> that conforms to the JSON value grammar.

http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf

This corrects the JSON grammar so that it conforms to the spec, and will correctly parse any legal JSON value, instead of only objects and arrays.

Merge pull request #298 from neuzrui/master

Fixed the issue with "expression"

Fixed the issue with "expression"
- Moved "ranking_windowed_function" and "aggregate_windowed_function" into
  "function_call", and placed them before "scalar_function_name ..."

  Now, aggregate and ranking function are part of the "function_call" and have
  higher precedence over user defined scalar functions.

  Previously, built-in functions like AVG, MAX, etc., were not being recognized
  as aggregate_windowed_function if they are not followed by an OVER clause.
  They both got recognized as user defined "scalar_function_name" because
  the "function_call" has higher precedence in "expression"

- Removed labels on "ranking_windowed_function" and "aggregate_windowed_function"

- Removed "over_clause" from "expression" since it's already included in
  "ranking_windowed_function" and "aggregate_windowed_function"

Fixed NPE during error recovery.

As indicated in https://github.com/antlr/grammars-v4/issues/113 the custom code responsible for token creation causes a NPE to be thrown when the parser tries to recover from errors.

2. original indentation spaces and line break chars are kept in the custom created token

Fixed operator precedence

Fixed operator precedence

Placed all operators inside the `expr` rule to get the expected operator precedence.

Changed:

    expr
     : ...
     | expr binop expr
     | ...
     ;

    binop
     : '+' | '-' | AND | OR | ...
     ;

to

    expr
     : ...
     | expr ('+' | '-') expr
     | expr AND expr
     | expr OR expr
     | ...
     ;

This completes the review of the Java7.g4 grammar in responce to Bug
report 7080366 : Grammar bugs in JLS7,
http://bugs.sun.com/view_bug.do?bug_id=7080366.

I do not believe that there are any more places where Java7.g4 is too
strict. There are still a few places where it is more relaxed than the
JLS7 grammar, but I judge them to require too much reworking of the
Java7.g4 grammar to be practical. In particular, the expression rule
sometimes allows too general of a subexpression. If someone wishes to
catch these particular syntax errors, they will have to do it in a
second phase scan of the parse tree.
